2 SENATE BILL 720
1 artificial intelligence tools are consistent with certain State guidelines each year the
2 Department to develop and publish a certain rubric and certain evaluative tools to
3 assist local school systems in the evaluation of artificial intelligence tools selected
4 for use by local school systems; requiring local school systems to procure artificial
5 intelligence tools consistent with certain provisions of law; requiring the
6 Department, in consultation with the Governor’s Workforce Development Board, to
7 ensure that artificial intelligence literacy is a component of workforce preparation
8 standards; requiring the Department to coordinate with the Maryland Center for
9 Computing Education and coordinators of professional learning and instructional
10 coaches to promote and implement certain training in artificial intelligence provide
11 certain professional development in artificial intelligence to educators and school
12 leaders; establishing the Maryland AI Education Collaborative on Artificial
13 Intelligence in K–12 Education; and generally relating to artificial intelligence in
14 primary and secondary education.
15 BY adding to
16 Article – Education
17 Section 7–2201 through 7–2204 to be under the new subtitle “Subtitle 22. Artificial
18 Intelligence in Education”
19 Annotated Code of Maryland
20 (2025 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
21 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
22 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
23 Article – Education
24 SUBTITLE 22. ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE IN EDUCATION.
25 7–2201.
26 IN THIS SUBTITLE, “ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE” HAS THE MEANING STATED
27 IN § 3.5–801 OF THE STATE FINANCE AND PROCUREMENT ARTICLE.
28 7–2202.
29 (A) (1) THE DEPARTMENT SHALL PROVIDE GUIDANCE ON ARTIFICIAL
30 INTELLIGENCE TO LOCAL SCHOOL SYSTEMS, EDUCATORS, PARENTS, AND STUDENTS
31 THROUGH AN ONLINE PLATFORM THAT:
32 (I) PROMOTES THE SAFE, RESPONSIBLE, EQUITABLE, AND
33 ETHICAL USE OF ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE;
34 (II) PROMOTES ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE LITERACY
35 THROUGH COMPUTER SCIENCE EDUCATION;

SENATE BILL 720 3
1 (II) (III) EMPHASIZES STUDENTS AND TEACHERS AT THE
2 CENTER OF EDUCATIONAL TECHNOLOGY;
3 (III) (IV) PRIORITIZES THE EDUCATIONAL NEEDS OF
4 STUDENTS USING EVIDENCE–BASED APPROACHES AND METHODOLOGIES; AND
5 (IV) (V) ACKNOWLEDGES TO STATE AND FEDERAL
6 STANDARDS ADDRESSES HOW STATE AND FEDERAL PRIVACY AND ACCESSIBILITY
7 STANDARDS APPLY TO THE USE OF ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE INSTRUCTION IN
8 SCHOOLS.
9 (2) THE DEPARTMENT, IN CONSULTATION WITH OTHER INTERESTED
10 STAKEHOLDERS, SHALL PUBLISH SEPARATELY ON ITS WEBSITE GUIDANCE FOR
11 EACH OF THE FOLLOWING GROUPS:
12 (I) STUDENTS;
13 (II) EDUCATORS; AND
14 (III) ADMINISTRATORS; AND
15 (IV) PARENTS AND GUARDIANS.
16 (3) EACH YEAR, THE DEPARTMENT SHALL REVIEW THE GUIDANCE
17 AND UPDATE THE GUIDANCE AS NECESSARY.
18 (B) THE DEPARTMENT SHALL DEVELOP STRATEGIES TO ASSIST COUNTY
19 BOARDS AND COUNTY SUPERINTENDENTS TO IMPLEMENT THE GUIDELINES AND
20 BEST PRACTICES DEVELOPED BY THE DEPARTMENT UNDER THIS SECTION.
21 (C) ON OR BEFORE 120 DAYS FROM THE DATE THAT THE DEPARTMENT
22 RELEASES THE GUIDANCE REQUIRED UNDER SUBSECTION (A)(1) OF THIS SECTION,
23 EACH LOCAL SCHOOL SYSTEM SHALL HAVE AN ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE POLICY
24 ALIGNED WITH THE GUIDANCE.
25 (D) (1) EACH COUNTY BOARD LOCAL SCHOOL SYSTEM SHALL DESIGNATE
26 A COORDINATOR BETWEEN THE LOCAL SCHOOL SYSTEM AND THE STATE ON THE
27 PRODUCTIVE AND ETHICAL USE OF SYSTEMS OF ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE IN THE
28 LOCAL SCHOOL SYSTEM.

4 SENATE BILL 720
1 (2) A COORDINATOR DESIGNATED UNDER PARAGRAPH (1) OF THIS
2 SUBSECTION SHALL BE AN INDIVIDUAL WHO IS EMPLOYED AT THE CENTRAL OFFICE
3 ADMINISTRATION LEVEL AS NONINSTRUCTIONAL STAFF.
4 (E) EACH YEAR, MORGAN STATE UNIVERSITY OR ANOTHER 4–YEAR
5 INSTITUTION OF HIGHER EDUCATION IN THE STATE SHALL SUPPORT THE
6 DEPARTMENT:
7 (1) IN EVALUATING A PRIORITIZED LIST OF ARTIFICIAL
8 INTELLIGENCE TOOLS SUBMITTED BY THE STATE SUPERINTENDENT AND SCHOOLS;
9 AND
10 (2) TO CERTIFY THAT ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE TOOLS ARE
11 CONSISTENT WITH THE STATE GUIDELINES.
12 (E) (1) THE DEPARTMENT SHALL DEVELOP AND PUBLISH A RUBRIC AND
13 OTHER EVALUATIVE TOOLS, AS NECESSARY, TO ASSIST LOCAL SCHOOL SYSTEMS IN
14 THE EVALUATION OF ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE TOOLS SELECTED FOR USE BY THE
15 LOCAL SCHOOL SYSTEM.
16 (2) THE RUBRIC SHALL BE DESIGNED TO SUPPORT LOCAL SCHOOL
17 SYSTEMS IN DETERMINING WHETHER ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE TOOLS ARE
18 CONSISTENT WITH STATE GUIDELINES.
19 (3) EACH LOCAL SCHOOL SYSTEM SHALL USE THE RUBRIC AND
20 OTHER EVALUATIVE TOOLS DEVELOPED BY THE DEPARTMENT IN THE REVIEW AND
21 SELECTION OF ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE TOOLS FOR USE WITHIN THE LOCAL
22 SCHOOL SYSTEM.
23 (4) THE DEPARTMENT PERIODICALLY MAY REVIEW AND UPDATE THE
24 RUBRIC AS NECESSARY TO REFLECT CHANGES IN TECHNOLOGY, LAW, OR STATE
25 POLICY.
26 (5) ON REQUEST, MORGAN STATE UNIVERSITY, OR ANOTHER 4–YEAR
27 INSTITUTION OF HIGHER EDUCATION IN THE STATE, MAY SUPPORT LOCAL SCHOOL
28 SYSTEMS IN ASSESSING THE TOOLS AGAINST THE RUBRIC.
29 (F) LOCAL SCHOOL SYSTEMS SHALL PROCURE ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE
30 TOOLS CONSISTENT WITH THE PROVISIONS OF TITLE 3.5, SUBTITLE 8 OF THE STATE
31 FINANCE AND PROCUREMENT ARTICLE.
32 7–2203.

SENATE BILL 720 5
1 (A) ON OR BEFORE JUNE 1, 2027, THE DEPARTMENT, IN CONSULTATION
2 WITH THE GOVERNOR’S WORKFORCE DEVELOPMENT BOARD, SHALL ENSURE THAT
3 ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE LITERACY IS A COMPONENT OF WORKFORCE
4 PREPARATION STANDARDS AND COMPUTER SCIENCE STANDARDS FOR
5 KINDERGARTEN THROUGH GRADE 12.
6 (B) (1) THE DEPARTMENT SHALL COORDINATE WITH THE MARYLAND
7 CENTER FOR COMPUTING EDUCATION ESTABLISHED UNDER § 12–118 OF THIS
8 ARTICLE AND COORDINATORS OF PROFESSIONAL LEARNING AND INSTRUCTIONAL
9 COACHES TO PROMOTE TEACHER PROFESSIONAL DEVELOPMENT TRAINING IN
10 ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE.
11 (2) THE TEACHER PROFESSIONAL DEVELOPMENT TRAINING SHALL
12 BE IMPLEMENTED STATEWIDE IN A TRAIN–THE–TRAINER MODEL RELATED TO
13 ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE LITERACY AND TECHNICAL EXPERTISE, WITH THE
14 INTENT OF TRAINING EDUCATORS BY JULY 1, 2027.
15 (3) (I) TEACHERS IN THE TEACHER PROFESSIONAL
16 DEVELOPMENT TRAINING SHALL BE COMPENSATED FOR THE TRAINING WITH TIME,
17 MONEY, OR RECERTIFICATION CREDITS.
18 (II) TEACHERS MAY NOT BE CHARGED TO ATTEND OR
19 COMPLETE THE TRAINING.
20 (B) THE DEPARTMENT SHALL PROVIDE PROFESSIONAL DEVELOPMENT IN
21 ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE TO EDUCATORS AND SCHOOL LEADERS THAT:
22 (1) IS SUFFICIENT IN DURATION AND QUALITY TO PREPARE THE
23 EDUCATORS AND SCHOOL LEADERS:
24 (I) FOR THE PROFESSIONAL USE OF ARTIFICIAL
25 INTELLIGENCE;
26 (II) TO APPLY ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE TO INSTRUCTION;
27 AND
28 (III) TO UNDERSTAND ETHICAL CONSIDERATIONS OF
29 ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE; AND
30 (2) PROVIDES SUBSTANTIVE COVERAGE OF:
31 (I) THE PURPOSE OF ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE IN
32 EDUCATION;

6 SENATE BILL 720
1 (II) BASIC ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE VOCABULARY AND
2 CONCEPTS;
3 (III) HOW ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE WORKS;
4 (IV) EFFECTIVE CLASSROOM USE CASES, INCLUDING TO
5 STREAMLINE ADMINISTRATIVE TASKS, TO SUPPORT SPECIALLY DESIGNED
6 INSTRUCTION, AND TO PROVIDE TIMELY FEEDBACK; AND
7 (V) EFFECTIVE USE, PRIVACY, SECURITY, ACADEMIC
8 INTEGRITY, AND MEANS OF AVOIDING OVERDEPENDENCE; AND
9 (3) IS OFFERED:
10 (I) DURING THE EMPLOYEE’S REGULAR WORKDAY AS PART OF
11 TIME DESIGNATED FOR PROFESSIONAL DEVELOPMENT; OR
12 (II) AS A COURSE THAT IS ELIGIBLE FOR CREDIT TOWARD
13 LICENSURE RENEWAL.
14 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That the Laws of Maryland read
15 as follows:
16 Article – Education
17 7–2204.
18 (A) IN THIS SECTION, “COLLABORATIVE” MEANS THE MARYLAND AI
19 EDUCATION COLLABORATIVE ON ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE IN K–12 EDUCATION.
20 (B) THERE IS A MARYLAND AI EDUCATION COLLABORATIVE ON
21 ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE IN K–12 EDUCATION.
22 (C) THE COLLABORATIVE CONSISTS OF THE FOLLOWING MEMBERS:
23 (1) THE STATE SUPERINTENDENT, OR THE STATE
24 SUPERINTENDENT’S DESIGNEE;
25 (2) THE EXECUTIVE DIRECTOR OF THE MARYLAND ASSOCIATION OF
26 BOARDS OF EDUCATION, OR THE EXECUTIVE DIRECTOR’S DESIGNEE;
27 (3) THE PRESIDENT OF THE MARYLAND STATE EDUCATION
28 ASSOCIATION, OR THE PRESIDENT’S DESIGNEE;

SENATE BILL 720 7
1 (4) THE PRESIDENT OF THE MARYLAND ASSOCIATION OF SCHOOL
2 PERSONNEL ADMINISTRATORS, OR THE PRESIDENT’S DESIGNEE;
3 (5) THE PRESIDENT OF THE BALTIMORE TEACHERS UNION, OR THE
4 PRESIDENT’S DESIGNEE;
5 (5) (6) THE EXECUTIVE DIRECTOR OF THE PUBLIC SCHOOL
6 SUPERINTENDENTS’ ASSOCIATION OF MARYLAND, OR THE EXECUTIVE DIRECTOR’S
7 DESIGNEE;
8 (6) (7) FIVE COORDINATORS DESIGNATED BY THE COUNTY
9 BOARDS UNDER § 7–2202(D) OF THIS SUBTITLE;
10 (7) (8) THREE REPRESENTATIVES FROM NONPROFIT
11 ORGANIZATIONS THAT REPRESENT PARENTS;
12 (8) (9) THREE REPRESENTATIVES FROM STUDENT
13 ORGANIZATIONS; AND
14 (10) ONE REPRESENTATIVE FROM A STATEWIDE ORGANIZATION THAT
15 REPRESENTS STUDENTS WITH DISABILITIES;
16 (11) ONE REPRESENTATIVE FROM A STATEWIDE ORGANIZATION THAT
17 REPRESENTS MULTILINGUAL FAMILIES AND STUDENTS;
18 (9) (12) THREE REPRESENTATIVES FROM LABOR UNIONS THAT
19 REPRESENT TEACHERS, ADMINISTRATORS, AND SCHOOL SUPPORT STAFF;
20 (13) THE PRESIDENT OF THE MARYLAND CHAPTER OF THE
21 COMPUTER SCIENCE TEACHERS ASSOCIATION, OR THE PRESIDENT’S DESIGNEE;
22 (14) THE EXECUTIVE DIRECTOR OF THE MARYLAND CENTER FOR
23 COMPUTING EDUCATION, OR THE EXECUTIVE DIRECTOR’S DESIGNEE;
24 (15) THE CHAIR OF THE GOVERNOR’S WORKFORCE DEVELOPMENT
25 BOARD, OR THE CHAIR’S DESIGNEE; AND
26 (16) ONE REPRESENTATIVE FROM MORGAN STATE UNIVERSITY.
27 (D) IT IS THE INTENT OF THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY THAT THE TEACHERS
28 APPOINTED TO EDUCATORS CONSULTED BY THE COLLABORATIVE UNDER
29 SUBSECTION (C)(6) OF THIS SECTION SHALL REPRESENT DIVERSE SUBJECT AREAS
30 AND LICENSURE AREAS, INCLUDING GENERAL AND SPECIAL EDUCATORS.

8 SENATE BILL 720
1 (E) THE STATE SUPERINTENDENT SHALL DESIGNATE THE CHAIR OF THE
2 COLLABORATIVE AND MAY ESTABLISH SUBCOMMITTEES OF THE COLLABORATIVE.
3 (F) THE DEPARTMENT:
4 (1) SHALL PROVIDE STAFF FOR THE COLLABORATIVE; AND
5 (2) MAY PARTNER OR CONTRACT WITH AN ORGANIZATION TO
6 SUPPORT THE COLLABORATIVE.
7 (G) A MEMBER OF THE COLLABORATIVE:
8 (1) MAY NOT RECEIVE COMPENSATION AS A MEMBER OF THE
9 COLLABORATIVE; BUT
10 (2) IS ENTITLED TO REIMBURSEMENT FOR EXPENSES UNDER THE
11 STANDARD STATE TRAVEL REGULATIONS, AS PROVIDED IN THE STATE BUDGET.
12 (H) THE COLLABORATIVE SHALL:
13 (1) STUDY THE USES OF ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE IN EACH LOCAL
14 SCHOOL SYSTEM, INCLUDING A REVIEW OF INNOVATION BY INDUSTRY AND
15 PHILANTHROPIC SUPPORT OF SCHOOLS IN THE USE OF ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE;
16 AND
17 (2) MAKE FINDINGS AND RECOMMENDATIONS REGARDING:
18 (I) THE DEVELOPMENT OR UPDATE OF THE GUIDANCE AND
19 BEST PRACTICES FOR COUNTY BOARDS UNDER § 7–2202 OF THIS SUBTITLE;
20 (II) THE IMPLEMENTATION OF BEST PRACTICES FOR RELEVANT
21 PROFESSIONAL DEVELOPMENT; AND
22 (III) THE ADOPTION OF POLICIES AND PROCEDURES
23 REGARDING THE DEVELOPMENT, PROCUREMENT, IMPLEMENTATION, UTILIZATION,
24 AND ONGOING ASSESSMENT OF SYSTEMS THAT EMPLOY ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE
25 BY A COUNTY BOARD.
26 (I) ON OR BEFORE JANUARY 1, 2027, BASED ON BEST PRACTICES FROM
27 ACROSS THE COUNTRY, THE COLLABORATIVE SHALL CREATE A DOCUMENT WITH
28 EXAMPLES OF ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE INTEGRATED INTO CURRICULA,
29 INCLUDING EXAMPLES FOR:

SENATE BILL 720 9
1 (1) ELEMENTARY, MIDDLE, AND HIGH SCHOOL CURRICULA; AND
2 (2) ALL SUBJECT AREAS REPRESENTED IN THE COURSES REQUIRED
3 FOR GRADUATION RECOMMEND A PROCESS FOR THE STATE BOARD TO UPDATE ON
4 A REGULAR BASIS RELEVANT STATE CONTENT STANDARDS TO ADDRESS THE ROLE
5 OF ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE.
6 (J) ON OR BEFORE DECEMBER 1, 2027, AND EACH DECEMBER 1
7 THEREAFTER, THE COLLABORATIVE SHALL REPORT ITS FINDINGS AND
8 RECOMMENDATIONS TO THE STATE BOARD AND THE ACCOUNTABILITY AND
9 IMPLEMENTATION BOARD AND, IN ACCORDANCE WITH § 2–1257 OF THE STATE
10 GOVERNMENT ARTICLE, THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY ON THE LEVEL AND QUALITY OF:
11 (1) PROFESSIONAL DEVELOPMENT OFFERED BY LOCAL SCHOOL
12 SYSTEMS AND PARTICIPANTS IN EACH PROFESSIONAL DEVELOPMENT ACTIVITY
13 DISAGGREGATED BY ROLE;
14 (2) STATEWIDE ADOPTION OF ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE GUIDANCE;
15 (3) THE USE OF ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE IN INSTRUCTION;
16 (4) THE INSTRUCTION ON ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE;
17 (5) THE USE OF ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE TOOLS;
18 (6) STUDENT SCREEN TIME PER GRADE IN EACH LOCAL SCHOOL
19 SYSTEM; AND
20 (7) (5) THE USE OF ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE IN
21 ADMINISTRATIVE TASKS.
22 SECTION 2. 3. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
23 June 1, 2026. Section 2 of this Act shall remain effective for a period of 2 years and, at the
24 end of May 31, 2028, Section 2 of this Act, with no further action required by the General
25 Assembly, shall be abrogated and of no further force and effect.

